====Verb====
{{en-verb|abus|ing}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To put to a wrong use; to [[misapply]]; to use [[improperly]]; to [[misuse]]; to use for a wrong purpose or end; to [[pervert]]; as, to '''abuse''' one's authority. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1856|title=History of England from the fall of Wolsey to the defeat of the Spanish Armada|volume=1|page=353|author=[[w:James Anthony Froude|James Anthony Froude]]|year_published=1870|passage=This principle (if we may so '''abuse''' the word) shot rapidly into popularity}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[injure]]; to [[maltreat]]; to [[hurt]]; to treat with [[cruelty]], especially repeatedly. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}
#* {{quote-book|author={{w|R. S. Thomas}}|title=At It|passage= And I would have things to say to this God at the judgement, storming at him, as Job stormed with the eloquence of the '''abused''' heart.}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To attack with [[coarse]] language; to [[insult]]; to [[revile]]; [[malign]]; to speak in an offensive manner to or about someone; to [[disparage]]. {{defdate|First attested in the early 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}
#* Macaulay
#*: The {{...}} tellers of news '''abused''' the general.
#* {{quote-book|year=1904|author= {{w|W. B. Yeats}}|title={{w|The King's Threshold}}|passage=But ever and always curse him and '''abuse''' him.}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To imbibe a drug for a purpose other than it was intended; to intentionally take more of a drug than was prescribed for recreational reasons; to take illegal drugs habitually. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 20<sup>th</sup> century.}}
# {{context|transitive|archaic|lang=en}} To [[violate]]; [[defile]]; to [[rape]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}
#: {{rfquotek|Spenser}}
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} Misrepresent; [[adulterate]]. {{defdate|Attested from around 1350 to 1470 until the mid 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1749|author={{w|Henry Fielding}}|title={{w|The History of Tom Hones, a Foundling}}|passage= Believe me, sir, he hath been '''abused''', grossly '''abused''' to you.}}
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[deceive]]; to [[trick]]; to [[impose]] on; misuse the confidence of. {{defdate|Attested from the late 15<sup>th</sup> century until the early 19<sup>th</sup> century.}}
#* '''1651-2''', [[w:Jeremy Taylor|Jeremy Taylor]], "Sermon VI, The House of Feasting; or, The Epicures Measures", in ''The works of Jeremy Taylor'', Volume 1, page 283 (1831), edited by Thomas Smart Hughes
#*: When Cyrus had espied Astyages and his fellows coming drunk from a banquet loaden with variety of follies and filthiness, their legs failing them, their eyes red and staring, cozened with a moist cloud and '''abused''' by a double object
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|Scotland|lang=en}} [[disuse|Disuse]]. {{defdate|Attested from the late 15<sup>th</sup> century until the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}

